    "summary": "The Garamantes (c. 400–200 BC at their early phase, continuing to 700 AD) were a Saharan civilization in the Fezzan region of modern Libya who sustained an improbable urban culture in one of Earth's harshest environments through a remarkable hydraulic engineering system (the foggaras) that tapped underground water to irrigate agriculture.\n\nThe Garamantes built an extensive network of underground irrigation channels called foggaras (similar to the qanat systems of Persia) that tapped aquifer water and brought it to the surface for cultivation. At their height, several hundred kilometers of such tunnels allowed the Garamantes to irrigate fields and support substantial towns in the Saharan interior. Their capital, Garama, was a walled city with temples and a complex urban layout. The Garamantes served as intermediaries in trans-Saharan trade, linking the Mediterranean coast with sub-Saharan Africa via their knowledge of desert routes. Romans knew them as fierce desert raiders and merchants; ancient sources describe their four-horse chariots adapted for desert terrain. Recent satellite imaging and archaeological work has revealed the extent of their foggaras system and substantially revised understanding of Saharan history.",
